  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Varicose veins affect a majority of adult patients and cause a decreased quality of life. In
      recent years, standard practice has been to perform thermoablation and local phlebectomies in
      the same procedure. There is conflicting data on the long-term outcome of the local varicose
      veins; there seems to be a need for more re-interventions if the local varicosities are not
      treated immediately. On the other hand, the prolonged combined procedure increases procedural
      pain and bleeding, as well as the risk for complications from deep vein thrombosis/pulmonary
      embolism.

      This trial aims to evaluate the need for immediate treatment of local varicosities and the
      potential sufficiency of main trunk treatment.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
